jchrest.architecture

Class VisualSpatialField

  • java.lang.Object
    • jchrest.architecture.VisualSpatialField

  • public class VisualSpatialField
extends java.lang.Object
    Implements a visual-spatial field, specifically one that handles attention-based imagery (see page 301 of "Image and Brain" by Stephen Kosslyn).

    Visual-spatial fields are 3D Lists whose first two dimensions represent the columns and rows of the visual-spatial field and whose third dimension maintains a history of VisualSpatialFieldObjects that have been placed on the coordinates denoted by the first and second dimension elements containing the third, i.e. [2][0][1] would return the second VisualSpatialFieldObject on coordinates (2, 0) in #this. The visual-spatial field's size is finite after creation (consistent with the view proposed by Kosslyn on page 305 of "Image and Brain)".

    Information in the visual-spatial field can be manipulated independently of the environment that the creator is currently situated in to test outcomes of actions without incurring these outcomes in "reality".

      • addObjectToCoordinates

        public final boolean addObjectToCoordinates(int col,
                                            int row,
                                            VisualSpatialFieldObject object,
                                            int time)
                                     throws VisualSpatialFieldException
        Adds object to the col and row specified in #this.

        If the coordinates specified represents an empty Square at the time specified and the object specified represents a non-empty square, the object will occupy the coordinates and the VisualSpatialFieldObject representing the empty Square will have its terminus set to time. In other words, empty coordinates become non-empty, if applicable.

        If the coordinates specified do not represent an empty Square, the object specified will co-exist with any other VisualSpatialFieldObjects that are alive on the coordinates at the time specified (see VisualSpatialFieldObject.isAlive(int)). However, if the object specified represents an empty Square, all VisualSpatialFieldObjects on the coordinates will have their terminus set to the time specified.

        Parameters:
        col -
        row -
        object -
        time -
        Throws:
        VisualSpatialFieldException - If any of the following statements evaluate to Boolean.TRUE:
        1. The object to add represents a blind square (invoking SceneObject.getObjectType() returns the result of invoking Scene.getBlindSquareToken()). This is because blind squares should be encoded as unknown squares in #this.
        2. The col and row specified are not represented in #this.
        3. The object specified represents the agent equipped with Chrest but there is already a VisualSpatialFieldObject that represents this agent on #this at the time specified.
        4. The object specified represents a VisualSpatialFieldObject that is already encoded on #this at the time specified, i.e. the result of invoking SceneObject.getIdentifier() on a VisualSpatialFieldObject currently alive on #this equals the result of invoking SceneObject.getIdentifier() on the object specified. This prevents issues when jchrest.architecture.Chrest#moveObjectsInVisualSpatialField( java.util.ArrayList, int) is invoked in context of #this.

      • getAsScene

        public Scene getAsScene(int time,
                        java.util.TreeMap<java.lang.Double,java.lang.String> unknownProbabilities)
        Parameters:
        time -
        unknownProbabilities - If a coordinate on #this does not contain any VisualSpatialFieldObjects that are alive at the time specified (see VisualSpatialFieldObject.isAlive(int)), the TreeMap passed here will be used to determine what SceneObject will be placed on the corresponding coordinates in the Scene generated.

        Keys must be between 0.0 and 1.0 (inclusive) and should always contain a key for 1.0. Values should be SceneObject types; the SceneObject constructed will have a randomly generated identifier (see SceneObject.SceneObject(java.lang.String)). So, an entry of [0.5, "A"] means that, if a coordinate in #this has no VisualSpatialFieldObjects alive on it at the time specified, there is a 50% chance that a SceneObject with object type "A" will be encoded on such coordinates in the Scene returned.

        Returns:
        #this as a Scene containing SceneObject representations of VisualSpatialFieldObjects that are alive on #this at the time specified.

        If a coordinate is occupied by more than one VisualSpatialFieldObject that is alive at the time specified, the one created most recently will be encoded as a SceneObject.

      • getCoordinateContents

        public java.util.List<VisualSpatialFieldObject> getCoordinateContents(int col,
                                                                      int row,
                                                                      int time,
                                                                      boolean returnUnknownIfEmpty)
        Parameters:
        col -
        row -
        time -
        returnUnknownIfEmpty - If no VisualSpatialFieldObjects on the coordinates specified by col and row are alive at the time specified, an empty List will be returned if this parameter is set to Boolean.FALSE. However, if this parameter is set to Boolean.TRUE a VisualSpatialFieldObject representing an unknown coordinate status is returned.
        Returns:
        All VisualSpatialFieldObjects on the coordinates specified by col and row that are "alive" at the time specified (see VisualSpatialFieldObject.isAlive(int).

        If the col and row specified are represented by #this, null is returned.

        NOTE: Modifying the List returned will not modify the actual contents of the coordinates in #this.
